Daley appeared a little lost on Laverne's first broadcast and said he felt "less valuable" than anyone else he grew up with because "it was not socially acceptable to like both boys and girls".
He said: “To this day, it is these feelings of being inferior and different that have been the real motivation and have given me the power and strength to succeed.”
He wanted to prove he was “something,” he said, so he didn’t disappoint everyone when they finally found out about his sexuality.
He is a two-time Olympic bronze medalist and has become a high-profile LGBT ambassador. He used his participation at this year’s Commonwealth Games in Australia to appeal for more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said he stands out because he feels he is lucky that he can live openly without negative consequences and wants to give others “hope.”
The three-time world champion said that the fact that he fell in love with a man - filmmaker Dustin Lance Black from the United States, whom he met in 2013 - "surprised me".
Daley married the Oscar winner, who is 20 years older than him, last year, but he said the age difference had never been a problem.
“When you go through so much at such a young age” – he attended his first Olympics when he was 14 years old, and his father died of cancer three years later – he said it was hard to find someone of the same age who had experienced similar ups and downs.
The couple became parents in June, to a son named Robert Ray Black-Daley, and Daley said his "whole perspective" had been changed.
“If you had asked me last year, it was all about me winning a gold medal,” he said.
“You know, there are bigger things than gold medals in the Olympics.
My Olympic gold medal is Robbie".
The son has the same name as his father Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 after being diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daley said his father did not accept that he would die, and one of the last things he asked was if they had gotten tickets to London 2012 – since he wanted to sit in the front row.
“I couldn’t tell him that he wouldn’t live long enough to sit in the front row,” he said.
“I held his hands when he stopped breathing, and it wasn’t until he actually stopped breathing and was dead that I finally realized he wasn’t invincible,” he said.
The following year, Daley competed in the 2012 Olympics and won bronze.
“I just knew this was what I’d dreamed of all my life – to dive in front of a home crowd during the Olympics, the best feeling ever,” he said.
It also inspired his first song choice – Proud of Heather Small – which meant a lot to him in the run-up to the Olympics and still gives him goosebumps.
