Germany's new warship delayed once again
The latest German navy frigate should have been completed in 2014 to replace old Cold War-era warships, but it won’t happen until early next year due to failing systems and galloping costs, local media reported.
The completion of the “Rhineland-Palatinate”, the ship of the brand new frigates of the Baden-Württemberg class, has now been postponed to the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit quoting a military spokesman.
The vessel was supposed to have been handed over to the Navy in 2014, but the major problems after delivery pursued the ambitious project.
The four vessels of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class navy ordered back in 2007 will replace the old frigates of the Bremen-class.
It has been agreed that they will be equipped with a powerful cannon, a number of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles as well as some stealth technology, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods – it should be possible to use the latest frigates for up to two years away from home port.
Constant delays mean, however, that the advanced warships – which were said to give Germany strength at sea – will already be outdated by the time they are put into service, Die Zeit reports.
The fateful F125 frigate created headlines last year, when the German Navy officially refused to put the vessel into service and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy has returned a ship to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little was known about the reasons for the return, but German media cited a number of important "software and hardware defects" that rendered the warship useless in a combat mission.
The software defects were particularly important as Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels will be operated by a crew of around 120 sailors – only half of the crew of older Bremen-class frigates.
It was also discovered that the ship has a huge overweight, which reduces performance and limits the Navy's ability to make upgrades in the future.
The 7,000-ton "Rhineland-Palatinate" is estimated to be twice as heavy as similar ships of the same class used by the Germans during World War II.
In addition to defective hardware, the price tag of the entire project – including training of the crew – has also started to become a problem.
It is claimed to have reached a staggering 3.1 billion euros – from the original 2.2 billion euros.
The problems surrounding the new frigates are of particular importance in light of recent warnings that Germany’s naval force is shrinking.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, the head of the German government's defense committee, confirmed that the navy is in fact "empty for usable ships".
The official said that the problem has escalated over time because old ships were destroyed, but no new vessels arrived.
He regretted that none of the frigates of the Baden-Württemberg class could be used by the navy.
The National Trust is listening to the secret life of bats
New research conducted at a land estate in the Scottish Highlands will reveal how bats use the landscape in their hunt for food.
It is hoped that the findings will shed new light on the behaviour of the unique flying mammals and help design future conservation measures.
The study for researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common bats and dwarf bats as well as brown and water bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at key locations around the property to track bat activity throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
Expert sound analyses of all recordings will determine the frequency of bat calls and which species do what.
Then a habitat map and a report will be prepared to create a detailed landscape picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, conservation adviser for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each of the species.
This information will be included in the decision on what measures should be introduced, such as the setting up of grazing grounds and how best to take care of the forest for bats and other associated species.
The bat population in Scotland and the United Kingdom has declined considerably over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and construction work that affects breeding grounds and habitat restriction.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a risk, the same with fly paper and certain chemically treated building materials as well as attacks from house cats.
Bats are not actually blind.
But because of their nocturnal hunting habits, they have more use for their ears than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use advanced echolocation to find insects and obstacles on the road as they fly.
The NTS, which is responsible for the maintenance of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
They have ten skilled experts who regularly carry out surveys, mapping breeding sites and sometimes rescue work.
The organisation has also established Scotland’s first and only bat reserve at Threeave land in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
Property manager David Thompson says the property is the ideal territory for them.
“Here at Threave we have a perfect area for bats,” he says.
“We have the old buildings, a lot of old trees and the ideal habitat.
But there’s still a lot we don’t know about bats, so the work we do here and at other properties will help us understand more about what they need to thrive.”
He stresses the importance of mapping the bats before maintenance is carried out on a property since the unintentional destruction of a single breeding ground can kill up to 400 females and young people, and perhaps outlaw an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, harass or disturb them or destroy their breeding grounds.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish employee of the Bat Conservation Trust, has urged the public to help in the work.
She says: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of the species we simply don’t know how the populations are doing.”
