Syria 'ready' for return of refugees, foreign minister says
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and appeals for help to restore the country, which has been devastated after more than seven years of war.
Speaking at the UN General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said the situation in the country is improving.
“Today, the situation on the ground is more stable and secure thanks to the progress made in combating terrorism,” he said.
The state continues to rebuild the areas destroyed by terrorists to restore normality.
All conditions are now simplified for the voluntary return of refugees to the country they had to leave due to terrorism and the unilateral economic measures that affected their daily lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the war began in 2011.
In addition, there are six million people still living in the country who need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would welcome help to rebuild the devastated country.
But he stressed that conditional assistance or assistance from countries supporting the uprising would not be accepted.
