Algae bloom update: Concentrations decrease in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fisheries and Wildlife Commission (FWC) shows a general decline in red algae concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, patchy blooms are reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier County – suggesting reduced concentrations.
A bloom of red algae extends about 210 km along the coast, from north in Pinellas to south in Lee County.
Spots are detected about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but fewer locations than last week.
Red algae have also been observed in Pasco County.
There have been reported medium to high concentrations at or off the coast of Pinellas County in the past week, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, natural to high concentrations in Manatee County, natural to high concentrations at or off the coast of Sarasota County, natural to high concentrations at or off the coast of Colsota County.
Respiratory irritation is still reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier County.
There have been no reports of airway irritation in northwest Florida over the past week.
